Imagine a large lump of clay named Lumpl.

The sculptor then forms it into a statue named Goliath.

Are Lumpl and Goliath identical?

Yes, they are composed of the same amount of the same physical stuff.

No part of Lumpl is not Goliath and no part of Goliath is not Lumpl.

If we wreck the statue and smush it into a great blob then Goliath is gone because part of the identity of Goliath is to be shaped like a statue but Lumpl remains because it has no set shape.

So on one hand, Lumpl and Goliath appear to be the same because they are the same exact thing just in different shapes.

But on the other hand how can Lumpl and Goliath be identical if one can exist while the other does not?

